<div type="translation" source="bib:Gillet2024_01">

<p>Fortune! Prosperity! This is the 19th year of Kōpparakesarivarman who has taken Madurai. To Mahādeva of Tiruvālantuṟai of Ciṟupaḻuvūr, the Brahman <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>brāhmaṇaṉ</foreign></supplied> Cāvānti Caṅkaraṉ Iravi of this town <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>ivvūr</foreign></supplied> gave <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>vaitta</foreign></supplied> to burn <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>eriya</foreign></supplied> night <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>iravum</foreign></supplied> and day <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>pakalum</foreign></supplied> one perpetual lamp <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>oru nontāviḷakku</foreign></supplied>, as long as the sun and the moon endure; [he] gave <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>vaitta</foreign></supplied> [for] one <foreign>uḻakku</foreign> of <foreign>ghee</foreign> <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>ney</foreign></supplied> by the <foreign>nārāyam</foreign> [measure] (<foreign>neyāram</foreign>?), [he] gave (<foreign>vai</foreign> &gt; <foreign>vaitta</foreign>) ninety <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>toṇṇūṟu</foreign></supplied> goats <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>āṭu</foreign></supplied>. <supplied reason="lost">This is</supplied> under the protection of the Panmāheśvaras.</p></div>

